This is not right. There is no "LocationCode" property in any Redfish schema. We are expected to use the ServiceLabel property within the Location complex (See: https://github.com/DMTF/Redfish/pull/4289)

This has been modified in code though.
Will paste the one with correct output once we are done with the interface required to publish location code.

These need to use their respective xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.* counterparts. We cannot have a com.ibm dependency here. If that means we need to publish new properties (like Model for CCIN ), we need to create those properties first.
OK, so we need to have interfaces to publish these properties.

None of this can be hard-coded, they can change from system to system and implementation to implementation. Please look at how we get the current data, say for Dimms, using the ObjectMapper (Ex: https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/memory.hpp#L829)

Super nitpick but we follow https://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/ and this is one of the 7 rules. 
For next time. 


    Separate subject from body with a blank line
    Limit the subject line to 50 characters
    Capitalize the subject line
    ***Do not end the subject line with a period ****
    Use the imperative mood in the subject line
    Wrap the body at 72 characters
    Use the body to explain what and why vs. how

But you already know the interface exists and have the service name and path not so sure this shouldn't be an internal error here. 
I'll let Ed chime in.
Yes, it should log an internal error.

It seems possible for it to occur in a race condition (interface is removed between calling the mapper and calling the service) so I think handling this silently better than posting a 500.

with that said, this is all super unlikely, so I don't care that much, and when it "fails" still gives a reasonable response, so I'm not too worried about it.
I am good with as is.

Can we drop VPD?
I don't see that used as a industry standard term and I don't think it helps describe what this commit is doing.

Why?

What would a SparePartNumber convey in the context of a BMC, which is generally soldered to the board, and therefore has no spare part?

Location->PartLocation->ServiceLabel looks like it's the exact property you added (not mentioned in the commit message), but it looks like you used a schematic location to fill it?  That looks incorrect to me, but I can't understand your intent without more detail here.

Model is meant to convey, the specific model of BMC on a normal system?  This seems odd that we would specify the chip.  Normally this field is used for conveying a rack managers specific model when it's a completely separate component in the rack.  In the context of the bmc, it seems a little weird, but again, I can only guess as to your intent without a good commit message.
Ack
Done
